  "trap": "Treating this as a generic positive matrix and trying Gaussian elimination on fractions is a swamp. The seductive error is to call it a Hilbert matrix and quote a memorised Hilbert formula — but the Hilbert matrix is $1/(i+j-1)$, not $1/(i+j)$; the off-by-one shifts the node sets and changes the answer. Identify the **Cauchy** structure $1/(x_i+y_j)$ with $x_i=i,\\ y_j=j$ and use the double-alternant formula.",
