     "Subtract the first block-row from the second: $\\to\\begin{pmatrix} A+B & B \\\\ 0 & A-B \\end{pmatrix}$; an elementary block-row operation, determinant still unchanged.",
     "The result is block upper-triangular, so its determinant is $\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)$. None of these operations used commutativity, so part (a) holds for all $A,B$.",
     "For the further step, $\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)=\\det\\big((A+B)(A-B)\\big)=\\det(A^2-AB+BA-B^2)$. This equals $\\det(A^2-B^2)$ exactly when $BA-AB=0$. Take the non-commuting nilpotents $A=\\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\\\0&0\\end{pmatrix},\\ B=\\begin{pmatrix}0&0\\\\1&0\\end{pmatrix}$: then $A+B=\\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\\\1&0\\end{pmatrix}$, $A-B=\\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\\\-1&0\\end{pmatrix}$, so the block determinant is $\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)=(-1)(1)=-1$, whereas $A^2=B^2=0$ gives $\\det(A^2-B^2)=0\\neq-1$. $\\blacksquare$"
