  "remark": "**Insight.** The headline factorization $\\det\\begin{pmatrix}A&B\\\\B&A\\end{pmatrix}=\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)$ is universal: block row reduction, or the symmetric/antisymmetric change of basis $T=\\tfrac1{\\sqrt2}\\begin{pmatrix}I&I\\\\I&-I\\end{pmatrix}$, block-diagonalizes the matrix to $\\operatorname{diag}(A+B,A-B)$ with no hypothesis on $A,B$. The genuinely commutativity-dependent step is the further collapse $\\det(A+B)\\det(A-B)=\\det(A^2-B^2)$, since $(A+B)(A-B)=A^2-AB+BA-B^2$ equals $A^2-B^2$ only when $AB=BA$. The two nilpotent Jordan blocks $A=\\begin{pmatrix}0&1\\\\0&0\\end{pmatrix},\\ B=\\begin{pmatrix}0&0\\\\1&0\\end{pmatrix}$ expose the gap with maximal economy: $A^2=B^2=0$ kills $\\det(A^2-B^2)$, yet $A+B$ and $A-B$ are invertible, so the true determinant is $-1$. The problem is a trap-detector: a student who 'proves (a)' by jumping to $\\det(A^2-B^2)$ is silently invoking commutativity they were never given."
