  "trap": "A natural misstep is to expand $\\operatorname{tr}(A^k)$ by brute matrix multiplication, drowning in $n^2$ entries. (It is not *false* — it does reach $t^k$ — merely a quagmire.) The slick path uses the scalar collapse $A^2=(v^{\\top}u)A=tA$: a rank-one matrix is its own eigen-machine, with a single nonzero eigenvalue $t$ and the rest forced to $0$ by rank. A second, subtler trap is to assert $\\det(I+A)=\\prod(1+\\lambda_i)$ \"by diagonalisation\" — but when $t=0$ the matrix $A$ is nilpotent and *not* diagonalisable; the product formula must instead be justified through the characteristic polynomial, which is valid for every $A$.",
