     "Left equality. $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)=\\|QP\\|_F^2=0\\iff QP=0$. Transposing, $QP=0\\iff (QP)^{\\top}=PQ=0$, i.e. every vector in $\\operatorname{im}P$ is killed by $Q$: the images of $P$ and $Q$ are orthogonal.",
     "Upper bound. By cyclicity and $P=P^2$, $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)=\\operatorname{tr}(P^2Q)=\\operatorname{tr}(PQP)$. Set $M:=PQP$. Since $I-Q$ is itself an orthogonal projection, $P-M=P-PQP=P(I-Q)P=\\big((I-Q)P\\big)^{\\top}\\big((I-Q)P\\big)\\succeq0$ and likewise $M=(QP)^{\\top}(QP)\\succeq0$. Hence $0\\preceq M\\preceq P$, so $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)=\\operatorname{tr}(M)\\le\\operatorname{tr}(P)=\\operatorname{rank}P$. By the symmetric argument $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)\\le\\operatorname{tr}(Q)=\\operatorname{rank}Q$, giving $\\le\\min\\{\\operatorname{rank}P,\\operatorname{rank}Q\\}$.",
     "Right equality. Suppose $\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)=\\operatorname{tr}P$ (the smaller trace). Then $\\operatorname{tr}(P-M)=0$ with $P-M=\\big((I-Q)P\\big)^{\\top}\\big((I-Q)P\\big)\\succeq0$, so the PSD matrix $P-M$ has zero trace and therefore vanishes: $(I-Q)P=0$, i.e. $QP=P$. Thus for $x\\in\\operatorname{im}P$ we get $Qx=QPx=Px=x$, so $\\operatorname{im}P\\subseteq\\operatorname{im}Q$. (Conversely $\\operatorname{im}P\\subseteq\\operatorname{im}Q\\Rightarrow QP=P\\Rightarrow\\operatorname{tr}(PQ)=\\operatorname{tr}P$.) Symmetrically, equality at $\\operatorname{tr}Q$ forces $\\operatorname{im}Q\\subseteq\\operatorname{im}P$. $\\blacksquare$"
