  "remark": "**Insight.** This is the base case of Hadamard's inequality, and the parallelogram picture is the whole intuition: a fixed pair of side lengths encloses the most area when the sides are perpendicular. Lagrange's identity is just the algebraic shadow of $\\sin^2+\\cos^2=1$, and the Gram-determinant viewpoint shows the bound is literally Cauchy-Schwarz in disguise, with the exact defect $(c_1\\cdot c_2)^2$ pinning down the equality case."
