  "statement": "Let $M=\\begin{pmatrix} A & B\\\\ B^\\top & C\\end{pmatrix}$ be a real symmetric **positive-definite** matrix partitioned into blocks, with $A$ of size $p\\times p$ and $C$ of size $q\\times q$. Prove **Fischer's inequality**\n$$\\det M\\;\\le\\;\\det A\\,\\det C,$$\nand show equality holds $\\iff B=0$.",
  "answer": "$\\det M\\le\\det A\\det C$; equality $\\iff B=0$ (the matrix is block-diagonal).",
  "trap": "Forgetting that $M$ being PD makes the **diagonal blocks** $A$ and $C$ PD too (so $\\det A,\\det C>0$). A tempting but wrong shortcut is to argue from $\\det M=\\det A\\det(C-B^\\top A^{-1}B)$ and claim $\\det(C-B^\\top A^{-1}B)\\le\\det C$ 'because we subtracted something' — that needs the subtracted matrix $B^\\top A^{-1}B$ to be PSD (true here) *and* the monotonicity $\\det(C-S)\\le\\det C$ for PSD $S$ with $C-S\\succeq0$, which itself must be justified. Subtracting a non-PSD symmetric matrix can actually *raise* the determinant, so the shortcut is genuinely invalid without these hypotheses.",
