     "**Determinant.** The recursion $d_n=d_{n-1}-d_{n-2}$ with $d_1=1,d_2=0$ gives $\\sum_{n\\ge 1} d_n x^n = \\dfrac{x(1-x)}{1-x+x^2}$. Using the factorisation $\\dfrac{1}{1-x+x^2}=\\dfrac{1+x}{1+x^3}=(1+x)\\sum_{k\\ge 0}(-1)^k x^{3k}$, the denominator $1+x^3$ forces a period-$6$ pattern in the coefficients, yielding $d_n=1,0,-1,-1,0,1$ repeating.",
     "The minus sign in the determinant recursion (inherited from $\\operatorname{sgn}$) is exactly what the permanent lacks: it turns the dominant pole at $x=1/\\varphi$ (exponential growth $\\Theta(\\varphi^n)$) into a pair of unit-modulus poles (bounded, periodic). Since $F_{n+1}\\ge 2$ and $\\det(B_n)\\in\\{-1,0,1\\}$, $\\boxed{\\text{they are never equal for } n\\ge2}$."
