  "statement": "For the $0$-$1$ matrix $M=J_n-I_n$ (ones off the diagonal, zeros on it), prove that the permanent equals the number of derangements: $\\operatorname{per}(J_n-I_n)=D_n=n!\\sum_{k=0}^n\\frac{(-1)^k}{k!}$, whereas the determinant is $\\det(J_n-I_n)=(-1)^{n-1}(n-1)$. Conclude that the two functions genuinely diverge: $\\operatorname{per}$ stays positive and grows like $n!/e$, while $\\det$ alternates in sign with magnitude only $n-1$; in particular for $n\\ge 4$ they differ in both sign-pattern and magnitude (at $n=3$ both equal $2$, the last coincidence).",
  "answer": "$\\operatorname{per}(J_n-I_n)=D_n=n!\\displaystyle\\sum_{k=0}^{n}\\frac{(-1)^k}{k!},\\qquad \\det(J_n-I_n)=(-1)^{n-1}(n-1).$ For $n\\ge 4$ the permanent (positive, $\\sim n!/e$) and the determinant (sign $(-1)^{n-1}$, magnitude $n-1$) disagree in both sign and size; $n=3$ is the final value where they coincide ($\\operatorname{per}=\\det=2$). $\\text{(proved)}$",
