     "Distinct eigenvalues $\\Rightarrow$ $A$ is diagonalisable as $P\\operatorname{diag}(\\varphi,\\psi)P^{-1}$; all such conjugates have $\\operatorname{tr}=\\varphi+\\psi=1$, $\\det=\\varphi\\psi=-1$. A repeated eigenvalue $\\varphi$ (resp. $\\psi$) would need a Jordan block $\\begin{pmatrix}\\lambda&1\\\\0&\\lambda\\end{pmatrix}$, but plugging it into $A^2-A-I$ gives the $(1,2)$-entry $2\\lambda-1$, which cannot vanish while $\\lambda^2-\\lambda-1=0$ — equivalently $x^2-x-1$ is squarefree. So the only repeated-eigenvalue solutions are the scalars $A=\\varphi I$ (resp. $\\psi I$).",
