     "\\textbf{Rank $0$:} $U=0,\\ W=\\mathbb{F}_p^2$ — one matrix, $A=0$. \\textbf{Rank $2$:} $U=\\mathbb{F}_p^2,\\ W=0$ — one matrix, $A=I$.",
     "\\textbf{Rank $1$:} choose a line $U$ (there are $\\tfrac{p^2-1}{p-1}=p+1$ lines through the origin) and a complementary line $W\\neq U$. Of the $p+1$ lines, exactly $p$ are $\\neq U$, and any line distinct from $U$ is automatically complementary in dimension $2$. So there are $(p+1)\\cdot p$ ordered pairs.",
