     "For traceless $M$, $M^2=-(\\det M)I$ (Cayley-Hamilton). Polarising, $MN+NM=-2\\beta(M,N)I$ where $\\beta$ is the symmetric bilinear form with $\\beta(M,M)=\\det M$. The anticommuting condition $AB+BA=0$ says precisely $\\beta(A,B)=0$: $A\\perp B$.",
     "On $V$, the quadratic form $\\det\\!\\begin{pmatrix}x&y\\\\ z&-x\\end{pmatrix}=-x^2-yz$ has signature $(1,2)$ (one positive, two negative directions). We need $\\beta(A,A)=\\det A=1>0$ and $\\beta(B,B)=\\det B=1>0$ with $A\\perp B$.",
     "But in a form of signature $(1,2)$, the orthogonal complement of any **positive** vector is **negative-definite** — it cannot contain a second positive vector. So two orthogonal vectors of positive norm cannot coexist. Contradiction; no real $2\\times2$ pair exists. $\\blacksquare$"
