  "statement": "For $n\\ge3$ let $W_n$ be the wheel graph: a central hub joined to every vertex of a rim cycle $C_n$, plus the $n$ cycle edges, so $W_n$ has $n+1$ vertices and $2n$ edges. Using the Matrix–Tree theorem together with the circulant eigenvalues of the rim, find a closed form for $\\tau(W_n)$, the number of spanning trees of $W_n$.",
  "answer": "\\tau(W_n)=\\Big(\\tfrac{3+\\sqrt5}{2}\\Big)^{n}+\\Big(\\tfrac{3-\\sqrt5}{2}\\Big)^{n}-2\\ \\ \\big(=L_{2n}-2,\\ \\text{a Lucas number}\\big).",
  "trap": "The trap is to delete the *hub* row/column when forming the reduced Laplacian and then try to diagonalise the remaining matrix as a pure circulant — but the rim Laplacian acquires a $+1$ on every diagonal from the spoke edges, so it is $\\,3I-A(C_n)$ on the rim, *not* the cycle Laplacian $2I-A(C_n)$. Forgetting that the spokes raise every rim degree by one turns each eigenvalue $3-2\\cos\\theta_k$ into the cycle's $2-2\\cos\\theta_k$; the $k=0$ factor then becomes $2-2\\cos0=0$, so the would-be reduced matrix is *singular* and its determinant collapses to $0$ — the absurd verdict that a wheel has no spanning trees, instead of the correct $L_{2n}-2$.",
