  "statement": "Let $A=J_n-I_n$ be the adjacency matrix of the complete graph $K_n$ (all off-diagonal entries $1$, diagonal $0$). For an integer $L\\ge0$, let $d_L$ be the number of closed walks of length $L$ starting and ending at a fixed vertex, and $e_L$ the number of walks of length $L$ between two distinct fixed vertices. Using the Cayley–Hamilton relation for $A$, compute $A^L$ explicitly, and give closed forms for $d_L$ and $e_L$.",
  "answer": "A^L=\\frac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}\\,J_n+(-1)^L I_n.\\quad d_L=\\frac{(n-1)^L+(n-1)(-1)^L}{n},\\quad e_L=\\frac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}.",
  "trap": "The trap is to diagonalise $A$ numerically and lose the integrality, or to assume $A^L$ has the form $\\alpha J+\\beta A$ and solve — forgetting that $A=J-I$ means the natural basis is $\\{J,I\\}$, not $\\{J,A\\}$, since $J$ and $I$ are the genuine idempotent-like generators. Worse: writing $d_L=(n-1)^L/n$ by 'the dominant eigenvalue' drops the oscillating $(-1)^L$ correction, which is exactly what makes $d_L$ an *integer* for every $L$.",
  "solutions": [
   {
    "name": "Cayley–Hamilton power-tower",
    "steps": [
     "$A=J-I$ has minimal polynomial from $J^2=nJ$: $A^2=(J-I)^2=J^2-2J+I=(n-2)J+I=(n-2)(A+I)+I=(n-2)A+(n-1)I$.",
     "So $A$ satisfies $A^2-(n-2)A-(n-1)I=0$, i.e. $(A-(n-1)I)(A+I)=0$: eigenvalues $n-1$ and $-1$.",
     "Write $A^L=p_L\\,J+q_L\\,I$. From $A^{L}=A\\cdot A^{L-1}$ and $A=J-I$, $J^2=nJ$: $A^{L+1}=(J-I)(p_LJ+q_LI)=(np_L+q_L-p_L)J-q_LI=((n-1)p_L+q_L)J-q_LI$.",
     "Thus $q_{L+1}=-q_L\\Rightarrow q_L=(-1)^L$, and $p_{L+1}=(n-1)p_L+(-1)^L$ with $p_0=0$, solving to $p_L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}$.",
     "Hence $\\boxed{A^L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}\\,J+(-1)^L I}$. Diagonal entry $d_L=p_L+q_L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L+(n-1)(-1)^L}{n}$; off-diagonal $e_L=p_L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}$."
    ]
   },
   {
    "name": "Spectral decomposition via idempotents",
    "steps": [
     "The orthogonal projection onto the all-ones vector is $P=\\tfrac1n J$ (so $P^2=P$), and $A=(n-1)P+(-1)(I-P)$ — eigenvalue $n-1$ on the constant vector, $-1$ on its orthogonal complement.",
     "Since $P$ and $I-P$ are complementary idempotents, $A^L=(n-1)^L P+(-1)^L(I-P)=\\big[(n-1)^L-(-1)^L\\big]P+(-1)^LI$.",
     "Substitute $P=\\tfrac1nJ$: $A^L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}J+(-1)^LI$, identical to the Cayley–Hamilton result.",
     "Reading entries: $d_L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L+(n-1)(-1)^L}{n}$, $e_L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}$. $\\boxed{}$ (E.g. $n=4,L=3$: $d_3=6$, $e_3=7$.)"
    ]
   },
   {
    "name": "Generating-function bookkeeping",
    "steps": [
     "The diagonal generating function is $\\sum_L d_L x^L=\\big[(I-xA)^{-1}\\big]_{11}=\\tfrac1n\\Big(\\dfrac1{1-(n-1)x}+\\dfrac{n-1}{1+x}\\Big)$ by partial fractions on the two eigenvalues.",
     "Extracting $[x^L]$ gives $d_L=\\tfrac1n\\big[(n-1)^L+(n-1)(-1)^L\\big]$.",
     "Similarly the off-diagonal generating function $\\sum_L e_Lx^L=\\tfrac1n\\Big(\\dfrac1{1-(n-1)x}-\\dfrac1{1+x}\\Big)$ yields $e_L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}$.",
     "Reassembling the matrix: $A^L=\\dfrac{(n-1)^L-(-1)^L}{n}J+(-1)^LI$. $\\boxed{}$"
    ]
   }
  ],
  "remark": "**Insight.** $K_n$'s adjacency is the cleanest 'two-eigenvalue' matrix, so every power $A^L$ lives in the $2$-dimensional algebra $\\langle I,J\\rangle$ — Cayley–Hamilton guarantees no higher powers are needed. The integrality of $d_L=\\frac{(n-1)^L+(n-1)(-1)^L}{n}$ is a baby instance of a *congruence*: since $n-1\\equiv-1\\pmod n$, the numerator is $\\equiv(-1)^L+(-1)\\cdot(-1)^L=0\\pmod n$. Any strongly-regular or distance-regular graph has the same phenomenon with more idempotents, computed from its association scheme."
